column4: "Easy Does It"
"Oliver/Young\012"

"'Easy Does It' - I think it was played originally by the Basie band. It is 24 bars long (8+8+8) - and the chords are all basically I iv ii V  in 2 keys (C then F then C again) and the challenge is to create variety by finding lots of ways around this wit\012"
"Walking bass on I.vi
column6: V - chord roots preceded by chromatic neighbour(s)"

column4: "Give each note its full value - one bass note is always  sounding"
"Note that pedal is NOT used over this walking bass line"
"Often chromatic neighbour tones are on the 'a' of a triplet - a one
"On a good piano go right down low - even to this bottom A"
"Finish with 2 handed  chord blocks -  LH plays rootless voicing
"Kind of simple stride style in LH"
"Notice that Pedal is used judiciously over stride LH  often 4 times per bar"
"LH and RH in unison 2 octaves apart for this Oscar Petersonish lick"
"Bass and Drums (brushes) in - First chorus play head"
"Little or no use of pedal - the drums and bass fill in the gaps when piano not playing"
"Oscar Peterson cliche - LH plays Dominant (G) on turn around"
"Drums to sticks - Improvised choruses begin - lots of Blues scale licks used"
"Modulating to F - using C half/whole dim scale on C7 chord"
"Descending F blues scale figure - note the use of 2 notes to accent"
"Tremolo continues as chords change under it"
"Common Blues phrase - repeated over different harmonies"
"Another cliche blues phrase"
"Another dim (half/whole) scale over C7 to modulate"
"Short Blues phrase is repeated but displaced on different beat"
"Head repeats - brushes return"
"RH white note glissando on G7"
"Piano"
"Bass"
"Drums - brush set"
